There are 3585 unique ids in this calendar table. The date, available and price columns are object data type. It might needed to be converted to other data type later. There are 665853 rows with no price and this rows with available equals to f(false).
I will seperate this table into 2 tables. One with data with price and available date. The other with data with NAN and unavailable date. I will use the latter one to find out on which month Boston are more busy and use the first one to calculate the average price each month.

In [6]:
def divide_table(df):
    '''Take the calendar datatable, return the df_1 which contains avaliable houses and df_2 which contaings reserved houses.'''
    # Convert date to timestamp
    df['date']=pd.to_datetime(df['date'])
    
    # Make a talbe with all unavailable date
    df_2=df[df['available']=='f']
    df_2['month']=df_2['date'].dt.month
    
    # Convert price to float
    df_1=df[df['available']=='t']
    df_1['price']=df_1['price'].str.replace('$','')
    df_1['price']=df_1['price'].str.replace(',','')
    df_1['price']=df_1['price'].astype(float)
    df_1['month']=df_1['date'].dt.month
    
    return df_1, df_2

Question1: In which season does Boston have the most visitors?¶

In [7]:
# Plot the two tables.
calendar_bos_avg, calendar_bos_nan=divide_table(calendar_bos)

fig, ax=plt.subplots(2,1,figsize=(16,9))

ax[0].set_title('Boston House Rental Number per Month')
sns.countplot(calendar_bos_nan['month'],ax=ax[0])

ax[1].set_title('Boston House Rental Average Price per Month')
ax[1]=calendar_bos_avg.groupby('month').mean()['price'].plot()
ax[1].set_ylabel('Average Price($)')

plt.tight_layout();

Answer:¶

From this plot it is obvious to see the most popular season to visit Boston is the fall. The most unpopular season is the winter. This is reasonable since the fall of Boston is beautiful and cosy, people could walk the freedom trail and even go to New Hampshire to visit white mountain. In winter, espically February, Boston is super cold. It is highly possible to have snowstorm, which makes visiting Boston a bad choice.
The price of rental also suggests this conclusion. From Septerber to October the average price is the highest in the year while in February the average price is the lowest in the year.

# Plot a heat map to see the correlations between numeric variables.

From the plot above it is clearly to see that with more accomodates, bathrooms, bedrooms, beds and guests, the price of house is higher. This is reasonable since the more people/rooms the bigger the house, which makes the price higher. The heatmap shows the correlation of these variables. Since the correlation is smaller than 0.95, I will use all these variables in building the model later.
It is intersting that the review score is not related with the price of houses. For this reason I will delete the review_score_value and reviews_per_month column when I build the model in the next section.

# Train test split.
X=listings_clean.drop('price',axis=1)
y=listings_clean['price']

X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.3, random_state=42)

scaler=StandardScaler()
X_train=scaler.fit_transform(X_train)
X_test=scaler.transform(X_test)
In [32]:
# Set early stop point.
early_stop=EarlyStopping(monitor='val_loss',mode='min')
In [33]:
# Build the neural network.
model=Sequential()
model.add(Dense(100,activation='relu'))
model.add(Dropout(0.1))
model.add(Dense(50,activation='relu'))
model.add(Dropout(0.1))
model.add(Dense(25,activation='relu'))
model.add(Dropout(0.1))
model.add(Dense(12,activation='relu'))
model.add(Dense(1))
model.compile(optimizer='adam',loss='mse')
In [34]:
# Fit the model.
model.fit(x=X_train,y=y_train,
          validation_data=(X_test,y_test),
          batch_size=64,epochs=100,
          callbacks=[early_stop])
